##The secret, the sad, the fearless stories, they all stayed in their cars

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

In addition to milk and cookies, the back seat of a driver often picks up gifts from doctors and nurses, sometimes a jar of rice pudding or a prized N95 mask.

By Lin Qiuming

Editor | Kim Zazu

By Lin Qiuming

Editor | Kim Zazu

1

Without the outbreak, Li Ming, 52, and his wife would be in Greece this Spring Festival. It was a long-planned trip for him and his wife, who had bought their tickets in advance for the Jan. 20 flight from Wuhan. On the 18th, they had an early New Year's Eve dinner. He received the news that someone had transferred the disease to Wuhan. He returned his ticket and turned to his wife. "

He decided to stay in Wuhan by himself, for which his wife still blames him.

Li Ming's vigilance is not without reason. He is a part-time Didi driver, he thought, if the outbreak in Wuhan, he will stay to help. In 2003, he signed up as a volunteer to fight SARS. That spring, he carried a 18-pound sprayer to the streets to spray disinfectant. Four hours back and forth, four pots a day, for over three months. He wore the most common disposable face mask and a disposable raincoat. "after SARS, what am I afraid of? "? "

On January 23rd, as Li Ming had predicted, public transport was shut down in the city, and car hailing services from various platforms were taken offline, forcing the city to press the pause button. A day or two after the city was sealed off, a group of civilian volunteers spontaneously set up a convoy to pick up and transport citizens, and were quickly stopped for safety reasons.

But the situation is serious, medical staff to and from work without a car, there are reports that some medical staff can only choose to ride a 2-hour shared bicycle to the hospital on duty. Another major hidden danger is also emerging. After the designated hospitals in Wuhan cleared out non-pneumonia patients, most of them took medicine at home or were transferred to remote hospitals. At the same time that medical resources were being squeezed out, if traffic was again blocked, they are at risk of going off their medication and interrupting their treatment.

To solve the problem of "Banning Traffic" , Didi Platform began recruiting local driver volunteers in Wuhan on the day of the city closure on the 23rd to take charge of the "ferry" work in the community and the hospital respectively. After the news was posted on the platform, li Ming and another Didi driver, an Fei, signed up immediately.

Li Ming

Li Ming is 14 years younger than her, and together with two other drivers, they form a community support team that ferries non pneumonia patients from the community to the hospital for injections, dialysis, and medicine and vegetables for the community. Wuhan, like them, has more than 1,000 volunteer drivers.

Community workers would forward the message to a group of four drivers and assign them tasks. Li Ming remembers that every time the community sent a request, all four of them posted in the group at the same time, "Damn it! "As in the old days, no one hesitated.

"take a patient to get an injection. "Once, Li Ming received a message from a member of the community.

He didn't know it was a brain cancer until he got there. She was paralyzed for several years. She was in a coma. She was completely unconscious. The left side of her body was rigid and she could not move her arm. Li Ming and her husband fitted her with sweaters and carried her downstairs.

Old House corridor narrow, but about 1 meter, can not stand side by side. The stairs are also steep, and patients are more likely to slide off a stretcher if it is used. They had to call a neighbor and another driver, with a sheet will her whole person, one pull a corner of the sheet, one after another down, will 140 pounds of her slowly moved to the car on the first floor. Four men walked nearly 20 minutes to a floor.

From the beginning of the New Year to the tenth, Li Ming repeated these moves every day. The patient was picked up at 9 a.m. , waited outside the hospital for her injection, and then drove her home at 12 a.m. One time, the I.V. held 500 milliliters, twice as much as usual. As they got out of the car, Li Ming noticed a puddle on his seat -- a patient was incontinent. He silently washed the urine stains with water and did not mention it to her family. "Oh, how can you say that? I'm a patient. "

Southerners like to eat leafy vegetables, green vegetables are a hot commodity in the supermarket, sold out by noon. The supermarket closes at 5 pm, and Li Ming closes at 5.30 pm. He has to rush through the gaps between orders to line up at a nearby supermarket and deliver food to the community. At the most time, he robbed more than 200 yuan of vegetables, happy.

The only thing harder than buying groceries is buying medicine. During the first few days of the siege, most of the pharmacies in Wuhan were closed, and Li Ming and his motorcade had to drive around the city's pharmacies, asking questions one by one. Once, for a particular prescription drug, the four of them worked from morning till afternoon.

The drivers are delivering supplies

2

On New Year's Eve, Jan. 24, the programmers on Didi's platform were in a similar state of anxiety.

After receiving the news of the closure of the city, they took the initiative and spent 31 hours to launch a new APP and install it in the APP's background. The APP allows medical staff to call a car on their own and see the location of the vehicle in real time. It's a lot faster than human deployment. As of February 9, Didi Wuhan Medical and nursing vehicle has been connected to 15 hospitals and 25 hospital districts, a total of more than 8,600 medical and nursing personnel.

Outside the program, there are living individuals. Working with Li Ming and Anfei to keep Wuhan running, is another team dedicated to supporting medical staff, the current number of more than 200 people. They were split up into small teams, stationed in different hospitals, transport medical staff to and from work, the cost of Didi to bear.

Hu Jianbin is one of the team leaders, his team has a total of 5 vehicles, docking Tongji Hospital Zhongfa Xincheng district, that is a treatment of critically ill pneumonia hospital.

Hu Jianbin's biological clock has been completely disrupted. Every day, he takes at least 10 or so orders, in order to take the night shift of doctors and nurses, he needs to sit at the hospital gate around 1 am, home to sleep at 3 am, get up at 7 am to continue to take the morning shift of medical care to work. Exhausted, he parked his car about two kilometers from the hospital and took a nap on the steering wheel.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hu Jianbin

He Mingrong is one of only two female drivers on the medical security team. Like Hu, she was one of the first 100 Didi drivers to sign up for the ride.

After the city was shut down in Wuhan, he mingrong insisted on staying. She sent her son and husband back to their hometown in Xinjiang, alone in a sports car in Wuhan. She was one of the few out-of-towners left behind. She spent New Year's Eve alone in a rented house. The company gave them each a "New Year's Eve dinner" , a tomato-flavored self-heating hotpot. "

The year before last, as a stay-at-home wife, she followed her college-age son to live in Wuhan. She laughed that she could only drive a car, so she became a Didi driver. "I love Wuhan. Before driving, just want to see more of the Wuhan scenery, last year my son and I went to see the Wuhan Sakura, very shocked. " She said, "but after Wuhan was shut down, it was completely changed. "

He Mingrong heard different cries in the car. A few days ago, she picked up a nurse from Tongji Hospital. The nurse, who appeared to be in her early 20s, was on her way to the hospital when she received a phone call and burst into tears. She told he mingrong, the phone is her colleague, a family of four there are two confirmed, the colleague and her mother-in-law into the isolation ward, leaving her husband and a two-year-old child. Now, the husband is also showing symptoms of cough and fever.

"What should I do with the doll? The nurse couldn't stop crying, and she and her colleagues panicked.

He Mingrong advised her, "doll resistance is good, first take him to check. ". You can't cry now. Encourage your co-worker, whose family is young and has a good chance of recovery. "She finished persuading the nurse, turning her head under her goggles and weeping silently.

At 10 a.m. One morning, an equally young nurse got into her car crying. The nurse had just become pregnant. Her husband and mother-in-law had returned home. She stayed in Wuhan and continued to work on the front lines. The night before, she'd finished her night shift, and she'd woken up with an unexplained stomachache. She trudged down the stairs to the maternal and child health hospital, but couldn't get a cab.

Getting into he mingrong's car, the nurse began to wail. I don't understand why all this is happening? "He Mingrong advised her a couple of sentences, and after a long while, she just recovered. Later, the nurse wiped away her tears and said to herself in a tearful voice, "I have to work the night shift today. I need a good rest and a meal before I can work the night shift. ". "

He Mingrong turned his head and studied her face. The nurse was only twenty-seven or eight years old. Ho ming-wing felt sorry for her. "Son, have you ever thought that the epidemic has passed and we won't do this? "? "The nurse shook her head with a pair of misty eyes.

I thought to myself, "she's just a child, and she can be so sensible in all this trouble. "I've heard so many stories about being a driver in this environment, " he said. At night, I can't even think about it, I can't start over, it's too hard, it's too hard. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ho ming-wing

3

Every morning at 5:00, Li Ming got up. Wuhan people are fastidious about "too early" . He cooks some dumplings or noodles for himself. It is an important meal of the day, because we don't know when the next meal will be ready.

The car smelled strongly of disinfectant, and wearing bright yellow protective clothing and masks, the whole figure was in a steamer, constantly sweating outside. He occasionally opened the window to let in some air, but after a while he became worried and quickly rolled it up.

Traffic Jams have been a topic of conversation in Wuhan since the city began its subway construction. But now the problem no longer exists, the street has not many pedestrians and cars, quiet only to hear the rain outside the sound of light hitting the car window. He is a native of Wuhan, but from this winter, he has become a bit of a stranger to Wuhan.

At noon, the driver of the social security team can go back to the community office and solve the lunch problem with instant noodles. The Medical Service convoy did not have fixed-point rest, only in the gap to charge the car, while waiting for charging, while looking for hot water noodles. It can be charged in 20 minutes, and they have to use a short break to finish their noodles in the cramped driver's seat and lie in the back for a few minutes when no orders have been placed.

Now, every Didi driver in Wuhan is afraid to see instant noodles again. No matter what flavor it is, the smell makes you sick to your stomach, but you have to eat it.

Didi regularly supplies them with protective clothing, face masks, disposable gloves and disinfectant. They spend nearly half an hour disinfecting the car before each trip, then don protective clothing and gloves. The mask is worn in two layers, and an N95 mask is worn over the disposable mask. The suit was damp and stuffy, and the mask was suffocating, but it could only hold for a full day. The cords on the masks often chafe the back of the ears, leaving drivers flustered by exposed wounds.

The shortage of materials has always been a common pain point in the fight against the epidemic. Didi Company in the rear for the first-line driver around for help, the company president Liu Qing in Weibo anti-epidemic materials for help post. Every suit is being guarded at the front and back. With no way of knowing when the next delivery will be, drivers will have to save as much as possible. When push comes to shove, wear a suit for three days, Spritz it with alcohol, put it in the trunk, and wear it again.

Protective clothing is not convenient to wear off, the inner layer once exposed to external air will be contaminated. Once, Li Ming had to pee in a hazmat suit because he had to pee in it. He later learned to drink only one glass of water a day before leaving the car, and to avoid going to the bathroom.

Every time you go back to the neighborhood, you wash your hands, like, 20 or 30 times a day. Li Ming's hands were red with frostbite. The frostbite broke. It hurts when I flush the cold water. In contrast to Li Ming, his hands were unusually white, and he sometimes rushed off on missions without gloves and had to finish his work before rubbing alcohol on it. Because of long-term and direct contact with alcohol and disinfectant, the original rough and hard hands were soaked soft, dry, no blood.

Didi drivers are delivering supplies

4

In addition to the material and work difficulties, the drivers have to bear more hardships. In a high-pressure environment, the pressure in the heart increases day by day. "Now that Wuhan is on the verge of life and death, there is not so much to think about. We are just doing it in silence. "He said.

On the day of the interview, he just finished a medical staff, parked in the parking lot of the community, and another member of the team to get him supplies, he rushed out of the car, did not expect the corner of the community flower bed, a careless, hit.

The rear wheel on the right side of the car knocked off a large piece of tile in the flower bed, and the car body was scratched nearly half a meter long. The scratch became a small straw that crushed Hu Jianbin. He sounded excited on the phone. "You know what? We have 10 confirmed cases in less than 25 buildings in our neighborhood, none of which have been admitted to hospitals. I have one in my unit. Have you seen a volunteer called he hui on the Internet? He used to be my leader, and he was always with me, and then a few days later, he was gone, and he was all alone, and there was no one there when he was cremated. There's no empathy, you know? "

He became more and more cautious. Over the past few days, he's parked in the basement, and he takes off his goggles and his hazmat suit before he goes upstairs. Now, he began to worry, what do not dare to take off, wearing such a bulging clothes to walk home.

Driving through the streets of Wuhan, he remembered reading a book by a French writer called "the vertical state. " "there are so many high-rise buildings in Wuhan, just as the book says, each one is a vertical street, is Spreading the virus. "

In the face of these pressures and fears, Hu Jianbin's approach is to "break his teeth and swallow them" and "let others see the positive side" . When the paramedics opened the door, he turned and shouted, "come on, " his customary goodbye.

Has signed up for this volunteer activity, an FEI has already more than ten days did not get along well with the family. He arranged for his wife and children to live with his wife at her mother's house, and saw them only once a day. After work in the afternoon, an Fei parked his car on the side of the road, his wife put the cooked food in the lunch box and handed it to him, the process is only a few seconds. "There are children and old people in the house, and I don't know who to take care of if I bring the virus to them. "

The child is only 4 years old, before Ann flew out of the car to come home from work, always hug him. Right now, he's just playing with him in the video. The day before yesterday, he and his wife said, "I haven't held him for half a month. ". "

"I had a family member who was diagnosed dead, and after he left that day, I realized I was really doing something dangerous. But someone has to do it, and if they don't, what about the patients in the community? We can't just leave them to die, can we? "said Alfy.

Li Ming and Alfy were in a convoy of five people. By chance, Anne flies to contact that to leave of driver, just know he has been quarantined. In the chat, he said to Anfei, "at that time picked up an old lady, no fever and any abnormal, also did not say sick, but after three days, the old lady because of the new crown has left. ". " When Anfei heard this, he was startled. "I thought, 'that's it. Who knows if the next passenger will be sick. "The only thing I'm thankful for right now is that I haven't had any contact with my family, and even if there is a virus, I'm fine. "

He was more worried about master Li Ming than himself. Although Li Ming, who has a long history of high blood pressure and diabetes, carries the pills with him, he knows that people with underlying illnesses, such as COVID-19 pneumonia, get worse. People close to him advised Li Ming not to do so, and he declined. "I think I'll be fine, " as he was in SARS, "and I'll hold out until the epidemic is over. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Didi community support motorcade

5

At the time of the outbreak, the back seats of more than 1,300 Didi drivers were carrying too much emotion.

A nurse pouring out her helplessness in a car, already struggling to care for a six bed patient alone, has been added to the two bed workload. Another nurse half jokingly described her first shift as awkward, Unfamiliar With the equipment, chaotic and exhausting, communicating with patients to calm them down. But more often than not, drivers see paramedics slumped in the back seat in silence.

I'll slow down the car so you can get some shut-eye. "Li Ming finished his community work and would also help with hospital orders. It was the only way he could calm the exhausted doctors and nurses.

He was impressed by a doctor who used to be a doctor. He walked on his own legs for three days before Li Ming picked him up and dropped him off at work. The Third Hospital in Wuhan, seven kilometers from his community, is a slow walker who walks three hours a day. On the fourth day of the Lunar New Year, he couldn't go on, so he called the community and asked Li Ming for help.

Li Ming asked him, "if you needed a car, why didn't you just tell us? " ? " "I don't want to trouble you, but I can't go any further. "Dr Tsang smiled wryly. Occasionally, he would slip Li Ming some milk and cookies and explain to him, "they're from the hospital. " . Li Ming knew that Dr. Tseng had lied to him about the milk, which came in eight gift boxes, and that it wasn't from the hospital.

In the silent city, care is also silent.

Ho has hardly met the rest of the team. She calls them "brothers, " remembers only their names and faces, and occasionally flashes them in group chats. But they each have their own way of calling out, honking if she sees a Didi sticker on the outside of the car. The other person will honk back to say hello. Then the two cars separated at the next intersection and headed for different streets.

They had 84 bottles of disinfectant in the car, but no alcohol. You can't buy alcohol anywhere in Wuhan. One time, she couldn't remember which brother had got a bottle of alcohol, so she shouted to the group, "I've got some alcohol here, at XX place, come and get it. ". "The passing driver took a small watering can with him to share. Everyone dared to take only a few deciliters, but not more. The alcohol was too precious to be left to other brothers.

Every night when she got home, she would announce to the group that she was home and was safe. The group of drivers, who had never met, had arranged to go out for a good meal when the epidemic was over.

Didi has built up a protective shield for its brothers on the front lines. Starting Feb. 11, Didi has been experimenting in Wuhan and other places by installing a protective barrier in the car of a ride-hailing service and putting a face mask on the vehicle. It looked like a transparent protective capsule for the driver.

They consult with health care workers and professionals, in the car to install plastic insulation film is more feasible, to a certain extent, can prevent the spread of droplets. In a public statement, Didi acknowledged that it was "a clumsy, even crude, approach at a time of crisis, " but was "willing to try many things" to protect first-line drivers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The protective barrier film inside the car

As the team captain Hu Jianbin spoke frankly, his concern for the team members came to some rough. A nurse chatted with him in the car. At Tongji Hospital, a driver in the sino-french new town area did not wear protective clothing and goggles. He was furious. "The sino-french new town hospital district is for critical patients, and the medical care is for high-risk groups. ". We've got other paramedics to pick up. What if we don't protect ourselves and infect others? "

He was anxious to send a message in the group, warning other drivers: "We are the next high-risk groups, must be highly aware of their own protective measures. "! " He said at the end, "we first medical team, must achieve zero infection, zero casualties, all the victory back ! " The message fills the screen, and these are only excerpts from it: "He was eager to protect his brothers in the convoy.

Over 200 paramedics, 1,000 community service members. I don't want to say I'm a hero, I'm just one of a group of images, just a group of images. "Hu Jianbin said.

On Feb. 8, Hu sent a friend circle to put the team's names on the screen -- "We don't have heroics, we have tracks. ". After many years, please remember these common names: Cao Chang, Huang Fei, Tong Liang, Liu Jinxin, he mingrong, Liu Qingzhou, shi-fei, Zhou Yikai, Zhou Shijun, Zong Tao, Liu Shucheng, Liu Qiubin, Wang Youwei, Bie Huarong, Li Yaping, Dong Hao, Mao Teng..."
